Topic:9 Package management:
---------------------------
.is used to install, update, configure and remove software.
.It ensures that software package and dependencies are handled properly and maintain(secure and manage their system efficently)	
	 
Example:
	
	.Web server -> serves websites (e.g., Apache, Nginx)
	.Database server -> stores and manages data (e.g., MySQL, Postgres, microsoft etc)
	.File Server -> stores and shares files between servers
	.Mail server -> handles emails (e.g., Microsoft Exchange)
	.Application Server -> runs business logics
	
EC2 server:
-----------	
	when you choose amazon Linux/debian/ubuntu/redhat/centos:
	
	Task:					Debian/Ubuntu:					Redhat/Amazon linux/CentOS:
	--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
	Update					sudo apt update					sudo yum update
	upgrade all packages	sudo apt upgrade				sudo yum upgrade
	Install package			sudo apt install packagename	sudo yum install packagename
	remove package			sudo apt remove packagename		sudo yum remove packagename
	List installed packages	apt list --installed			yum list installed
	
Key Features & Functions:
-------------------------
	.Install: add new software
	.Upgrade: update installed packages
	.Remove: Uninstall software

Protocols:
----------
Inbound rules: 	ssh(secure shell used to connect linux, 22
				http(hypertext transport protocol, used to access unsecured websites, port 80
				https(hypertext transport protocol secure, used to access secured websites, port 443
				RDP; remote desk protocol only windows
				mysql
Outbound rules:All traffic


TOPIC:10 Service Management:
----------------------------
you can start, stop, restart and monitor services 

Key service managment commands:
-------------------------------
For Example:
	
Action:					Command Example:
----------------------------------------
start service			sudo systemctl start service
stop service			sudo systemctl stop service
restart service			sudo systemctl restart service

Examples:
	.Start Apache: sudo systemctl start nginx/apache/httpd
	.stop Apache: sudo systemctl stop httpd
	.restart Apache: sudo systemctl restart httpd
				

Topic:11 user management in Linux:
----------------------------------
.Manage users and groups using command-line tools
.Create, modify, view and delete users and groups
.groups nothing but collection of users

Creating users:
	.useradd/adduser: Adding new user (ex: useraddd shiva)
	 shiva:!!:20413:0:99999:7:::
	a)shiva: This is the username you created
	b)!!: password is locked or not set 
	C)20413: date when the password was last changed
	d)0:Minimum days between password changes
	e)99999: Maximum days before password expires
	f)7: Warining period before password ecpiry
	g)::: = inactivity or account expiry
	
Setting and managing passwords:
	.passwd: set or change user password (Ex: psswd shiva/kumar)
	
logging to account using username and password:
	.su username
	
To view all users:
	.cat /etc/shadow
	.cat /etc/passwd
	
Deleting Users:
	.userdel: delete user (Ex: userdel shiva/kumar)
	.deluser: Delete user and thier files (Ex: deluser shiva/kumar)
	
Viewing user information:
	.id: show users UID and group IDs (Ex: id shiva)

Group management:
-----------------
	.groupadd: Adding new group (ex: groupadd groupname)
	.cat /etc/group: checking group exit or not
	.usermod: Add user to a group (ex: usermod -aG groupname username)
	.groupdel: Delete group (ex: groupdel groupname)
